4. Write a Python program student_marks_analyzer.py that asks the user to enter the number of
students in a class.Then ask the user to enter the marks (0–100) for each student, one by one,
and store all the marks so that they can be processed later. After all marks are entered, the
program should display:
● The list of all marks entered.      ● The total of all marks.    ● The average marks of the class 
● The highest and lowest marks in the class.     ● How many students passed (marks ≥ 40).
● How many students failed (marks < 40).   ● Display the marks in reverse order of entry.
● Display only those marks that are even numbers.

marks = list(map(int, input("Enter marks: ").split()))
print("Marks entered: ", marks)
print(f"Total Marks: {sum(marks)}")
print(f"Average Marks: {sum(marks)/len(marks)}")
print(f"Highest Mark: {max(marks)}")
print(f"Lowest Mark: {min(marks)}")
pass_count = 0
for i in range(len(marks)):
    if marks[i] >= 40:
        pass_count += 1
print(f"{pass_count} students passed")
fail_count = 0
for i in range(len(marks)):
    if marks[i] < 40:
        fail_count += 1
print(f"{fail_count} students failed")
pass_c1 = [i for i in marks if i >= 40]
print(f"{len(pass_c1)} students passed")
fail_c1 = [i for i in marks if i < 40]
print(f"{len(fail_c1)} students failed")
pass_c2 = sum(1 for i in marks if i >= 40)
print(f"{pass_c2} students passed")
fail_c2 = sum(1 for i in marks if i < 40)
print(f"{fail_c2} students failed")
print(f"Marks in reversed order: {marks[::-1]}")
even_marks = [i for i in marks if i % 2 == 0]
print("Even Marks:", even_marks)
